 \section{method}\label{sec:method}

\subsection{Simulation}

For the analysis we use the MICE Grand Challenge simulation \citep{Fosalba2015,Fosalba2015b,Crocce2015}, an N-body simulation of a $\Lambda$CDM cosmology with the following cosmological parameters: $\Omega_m = 0.25$, $\sigma_8 = 0.8$, $n_s = 0.95$, $\Omega_b = 0.044$, $\Omega_\Lambda = 0.75$, $h = 0.7$. It has a volume of $(3.072{\, h^{-1} \, {\rm Gpc}})^3$ with $4096^3$ particles of mass $2.927\times 10^{10}{\, h^{-1} \, {\rm M_{\odot}}}$. The galaxy catalogue has been run according to a Halo Occupation Distribution (HOD) and a SubHalo Abundance Matching (SHAM) prescriptions \citep{Carretero2015}. The parameters of the model have been fitted to reproduce clustering as a function of luminosity and colour from the Sloan Digital Sky Survey \citep{Zehavi2011}, as well as the luminosity function \citep{Blanton2003,Blanton2005b} and colour-magnitude diagrams \citep{Blanton2005c}. We use the MICECATv2 catalogue, an extension of the publicly available MICECATv1 catalogue\footnote{\texttt{http://cosmohub.pic.es/}}.  The galaxy catalogue is complete for $i<24$ from $z = 0.07$ to $z = 1.4$. The catalogue also contains the lensing quantities ($\gamma_1$, $\gamma_2$ and $\kappa$) at the position of each galaxy, calculated from the dark matter field with a resolution of Nside=8192 in healpix (corresponding to a pixel size of $\sim 0.43$ arcmin), so the lensing quantities of the galaxies do not have shape noise. 

